    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The main argument against labor unions is that they can stifle economic growth and innovation by demanding higher wages and benefits, which can lead to increased costs for businesses. This, in turn, can result in higher prices for consumers and potentially less hiring, as companies may struggle to afford the additional expenses. Critics also argue that unions can be inflexible, making it difficult for businesses to adapt to changing market conditions. Additionally, some believe that unionized workers receive more generous compensation than their non-unionized counterparts, which can create wage disparities and hinder merit-based promotions. Overall, opponents contend that unions can hinder competitiveness and economic efficiency.",
